    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Goblin rule\"? Oh, you want the pure, unadulterated syntax, stripped bare of any charmingly chaotic goblin analogies? Fine. I can do that. It's like trying to teach a goblin to file its taxes—possible, but dreadfully tedious.\n\nAttachment preference, in formal syntax, refers to the tendency of a language to prefer one structural attachment over another when multiple interpretations are grammatically possible. It's not a hard rule, but a statistical tendency observed in large corpora.\n\nWhen you have a structure like $\\text{VP} + \\text{PP}$ or $\\text{NP} + \\text{PP}$, the preference often leans towards **local attachment**—meaning the PP attaches to the closest possible constituent. In your example, \"with the telescope,\" the NP (\"the man\") is closer to the PP than the VP (\"saw the man\"). So, the default, or preferred, reading is often that the PP modifies the NP (the man has the telescope).\n\nHowever, this preference is not absolute. The VP attachment is often favored when the semantic role of the PP fits the action of the verb. If the verb implies an instrument (like *cut* or *see*),",
      "source": "target",
